nodes.bodyText:
Well, there are really three different use-cases here.
1/ Keeping the behaviour but altering annotations:
public interface AuthorController extends PanacheCrudController<Author, Long> {
// TODO: are the original annotations inherited? @GET, etc…
  @Metered
  @RolesAllowed("READER")
  @Operation(summary = "List all authors")
  @Override
  Response list();
}
2/ Changing the behaviour by delegating to original impl:
public interface AuthorController extends PanacheCrudController<Author, Long> {
// TODO: original annotations?
  @Metered
  @RolesAllowed("READER")
  @Operation(summary = "List all authors")
  @Override
  default Response list(){
    Logger.info("We're doing a list, baby, yeah!");
    return PanacheCrudController::super.list(); // ATM this won't fly since it's not default
  }
}
3/ Changing the behaviour entirely:
public interface AuthorController extends PanacheCrudController<Author, Long> {
// TODO: original annotations?
  @Metered
  @RolesAllowed("READER")
  @Operation(summary = "List all authors")
  @SomeAnnotationToSayThisReplacesList
  default Response list(@QueryParam String user){
    Logger.info("We're doing a list for %s, baby, yeah!", user);
    return Response.ok(Author.byName(user).list()).build();
  }
}
All three use-cases have open questions:
1/ Do we have to repeat the original annotations? I guess yes otherwise we can't change/remove them
2/ How can we delegate to the original method? ATM we can't because the method is not defaulted, and if it's not we can't invoke it. Supporting the use-case from 3/ would allow us to specify the new method with a new name and still generate (and manually invoke) the original method (unexposed).
3/ We need an annotation to specify that this method replaces another one, but it allows us to extend the parameters and solve 2/ as well.
None of those requirements force us towards any direction as to how to disable one method (as opposed to altering it), and so I still think an annotation on the class is easier than specifying the signature just to remove it. It feels really awkward.

